   ## GLOBAL FIX
   To prevent this class of bugs, consider using smart pointers (e.g.,
   `std::shared_ptr` or `std::unique_ptr`) and checking pointers before usage.
   Implement constructors that ensure all pointers are either valid or handled
   carefully (e.g., through initialization lists in constructors). The use of
   safe accessors that encapsulate pointer access with null checks can also
   minimize such errors. Moreover, utilizing modern C++ features like Optionals
   (`std::optional`) can signal explicitly when a value might not be present,
   avoiding the pitfalls of raw pointers.
